[The AI situation in Japan is indeed ambiguous. Between 27 Jun and 6 Dec
2005, Japan sent 7 reports to the OIE on the identification of "a
low-pathogenic H5N2 A influenza virus" on about 40 poultry farms,
reportedly lingering in Ibaraki district since April 2005. In the absence
of clinical symptoms, the diagnosis was based upon serology and virology.
The illegal use of a deficient vaccine, which might have included a live
virus, was mentioned earlier as a suspected but not (officially) proven
cause of the event (see item [3] in 20051031.3174).
Recently, 77 poultry workers from the affected farms have been found
sero-positive to the H5N2 virus.
It has been reported that an advisory team nominated by Japan's
Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries Ministry was expected to deliver its
official report in November 2005. Elucidating information on this unusual
event will be helpful. - Mod.AS]
